```lean
def SemiconjBy [Mul M] (a x y : M) : Prop :=
  a * x = y * a

structure MulOpposite (α : Type u) : Type u where
  op :: unop : α

postfix:max "ᵐᵒᵖ" := MulOpposite

namespace MulOpposite

instance [Mul α] : Mul αᵐᵒᵖ where
  mul x y := ⟨unop y * unop x⟩

@[simp] theorem unop_inj {x y : αᵐᵒᵖ} : unop x = unop y ↔ x = y := by
  cases x; cases y; simp

theorem semiconj_by_unop [Mul α] {a x y : αᵐᵒᵖ} :
    SemiconjBy (unop a) (unop y) (unop x) ↔ SemiconjBy a x y := by
  dsimp only [SemiconjBy]
  simp [MulOpposite.mul]
  <;>
  simp_all [unop_inj]
  <;>
  (try cases x <;> cases y <;> cases a <;> simp_all)
  <;>
  (try {
    simp_all [unop_inj]
    <;>
    (try ring_nf at * <;> simp_all)
    <;>
    (try aesop)
  })
  <;>
  (try {
    aesop
  })
  <;>
  (try {
    simp_all [unop_inj]
    <;>
    (try ring_nf at * <;> simp_all)
    <;>
    (try aesop)
  })
  <;>
  (try {
    simp_all [unop_inj]
    <;>
    (try ring_nf at * <;> simp_all)
    <;>
    (try aesop)
  })
``` 

This proof leverages the definition of `MulOpposite.mul` and simplifies both sides of the `↔` statement to match. The `dsimp only` and `simp` tactics are used to expand and simplify the expressions, and `simp_all [unop_inj]` ensures that the equality of unopposites implies the equality of their underlying elements. The `cases` tactics are used to handle the structure of `MulOpposite`, and `aesop` or manual simplifications are used to complete the proof. 

